          "body": "5:13 states the letter’s purpose explicitly: *that you may know that you have eternal life*. Assurance is the goal, not a presumption — and it flows from the objective testimony just rehearsed, not from inner feelings. Two consequences follow. First, *parresia* — bold confidence in prayer (5:14-15) — because we know God hears requests made according to His will. Second, intercession for a sinning brother (5:16-17): the believer who sees a brother sinning *asks*, and God gives life. The *sin leading to death* (5:16) is debated among orthodox interpreters — Calvin and Stott read it as deliberate apostasy paralleling the secessionists’ departure (2:19); Augustine read it as final impenitence; some read it as physical death under divine discipline (cf. 1 Cor 11:30). The chapter does not require us to identify the sin precisely; it tells us *not* to make this category an excuse for inaction toward a brother whose sin is not of that kind."
