          "title": "Three closing certainties (5:18-20)",
          "body": "John’s closing rhetoric is three stacked *oidamen* statements. **We know** that the one born of God does not keep on sinning, because the One born of God (Christ — most likely the Greek subject of *teretei auton*) keeps him, and the evil one does not touch him (5:18). **We know** that we are of God, while the whole world lies in the power of the evil one (5:19) — a sober cosmic dualism that defines the believer’s situation in the world. **We know** that the Son of God has come and has given us *dianoia* (understanding) to know the True One — and we are in the True One, in His Son Jesus Christ; *this* is the true God and eternal life (5:20). The last clause is one of the New Testament’s most direct affirmations of Christ’s deity; the natural antecedent of *houtos* (this) is the nearest noun, *Jesus Christ*."
